{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618627"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:24:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:24:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16512"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16512"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9203"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50982"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7659"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21830"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following neural pathways best explains the pain-relieving effect of mechanical stimulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interneuron","GABA-ergic neuron","Cholinergic neuron","Sensory neuron","Motor neuron"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gate control theory of pain, proposed by Melzack and Wall, explains how non-noxious mechanical stimuli can reduce pain perception. When large diameter mechanosensitive A\u03b2 fibres are activated (such as through rubbing or massage), they stimulate \u003Cstrong\u003Einterneurons\u003C/strong\u003E in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord. These inhibitory interneurons then suppress the transmission of pain signals from small diameter nociceptive fibres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGABA-ergic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E are indeed inhibitory neurons, but this term specifically refers to their neurotransmitter rather than their functional role in the gate control theory. While some inhibitory interneurons in the dorsal horn may use GABA as a neurotransmitter, this is not the key concept being tested.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholinergic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E use acetylcholine as their neurotransmitter and are not specifically involved in the gate control mechanism of pain modulation at the spinal cord level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory neurons\u003C/strong\u003E carry information from the periphery to the central nervous system but are not responsible for the inhibitory effects described in gate control theory.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMotor neurons\u003C/strong\u003E are responsible for muscle contraction and are not involved in pain modulation through the gate control mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis mechanism explains common experiences such as why rubbing a bumped elbow or applying pressure to a painful area can provide temporary relief. The activation of mechanoreceptors essentially \u0027closes the gate\u0027 to pain transmission through the action of inhibitory interneurons.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gate control theory explains how non-noxious mechanical stimuli can reduce pain perception through activation of inhibitory interneurons in the dorsal horn.","Large diameter mechanosensitive A\u03b2 fibres activate inhibitory interneurons that suppress pain transmission from small diameter nociceptive fibres.","This mechanism explains why rubbing a painful area can provide temporary pain relief."],"references":["Fishell G, Kepecs A. Interneuron Types as Attractors and Controllers. Annu Rev Neurosci. 2020 Jul 8;43:1-30. doi: 10.1146/annurev-neuro-070918-050421. Epub 2019 Jul 12. PMID: 31299170; PMCID: PMC7064158.","Yang J, Yang X, Tang K. Interneuron development and dysfunction. FEBS J. 2022 Apr;289(8):2318-2336. doi: 10.1111/febs.15872. Epub 2021 Apr 23. PMID: 33844440.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16512"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T15:24:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T12:02:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9203"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65543"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description